response.summary: Gender incongruence (GI) refers to the feeling that the physical characteristics of the body are not in line with the...
response.text: Gender incongruence (GI) refers to the feeling that the physical characteristics of the body are not in line with the experienced gender. This may (in the case of gender dysphoria) or may not be accompanied by distress.
response.source: Kreukels, B. P., & Guillamon, A. (2016). Neuroimaging studies in people with gender incongruence. International Review Of Psychiatry, 28(1), 120-128. doi:10.3109/09540261.2015.1113163

response.summary: Over the years, terminology has frequently been changed. If identities or behaviours are not in line with a person’s natal sex,...
response.text: Over the years, terminology has frequently been changed. If identities or behaviours are not in line with a person’s natal sex, we will use the term ‘gender incongruent’; ‘transgender’ will be used as an umbrella term to refer to all kinds of phenomena related to gender incongruence. […] If a person experiences distress resulting from incongruence between gender identity and assigned gender (which happens usually at birth), this person is gender dysphoric.
response.source: F. Beek, T., Cohen-Kettenis, P. T., & Kreukels, B. P. (2016). Gender incongruence/gender dysphoria and its classification history. International Review Of Psychiatry, 28(1), 5-12. doi:10.3109/09540261.2015.1091293

response.summary: Another diagnostic exclusion factor was the clinically significant distress or social impairment criterion that must be met for...
response.text: Another diagnostic exclusion factor was the clinically significant distress or social impairment criterion that must be met for a positive diagnosis in both the DSM-5 (Criteria B) and the ICD-10 (Criteria D). However, among health professionals who assist transgender people, it is understood that the anxiety and inadequacy felt by transsexuals is mainly a result of the conflict between the individual’s and society’s moral values, which is also the source of the prejudice and social stigma to which they are culturally exposed. It is believed that in some families and social contexts, transgender people can be protected from prejudice and, consequently, from social suffering.
response.source: Soll, B. M., Robles-García, R., Brandelli-Costa, A., Mori, D., Mueller, A., Vaitses-Fontanari, A. M., & … Lobato, M. (2018). Gender incongruence: a comparative study using ICD-10 and DSM-5 diagnostic criteria. Revista Brasileira De Psiquiatria, 40(2), 174-180. doi:10.1590/1516-4446-2016-2224

response.summary: Why don’t people realize that identifying openly as a binary trans person, not having been through any transition and presenting...
response.body:
Why don’t people realize that identifying openly as a binary trans person, not having been through any transition and presenting very strongly as one’s assigned gender gives off a strong vibe of “liar”?

Doing that would induce unbearable gender dysphoria if you actually are trans. It’s straight up contradictory.
